Let's use the determinant method to find the equation of the plane. The plane can be determined by the cross product of two vectors that lie in the plane. (\textit{See method in} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_in_three_dimensions#Determining_plane_equation for details.)<end think>
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{u} &= \begin{pmatrix}
1-(-3) \\
4-4 \\
0-(-2)  
\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 0 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \\
\mathbf{v} &= \begin{pmatrix}
3-(-3) \\
2-4 \\
-1-(-2)
\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ -2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}We solve \(\mathbf{n} = \mathbf{u} \times \mathbf{v}\) to find the normal vector \(\mathbf{n}\) to the plane:
\[\mathbf{n} = \begin{pmatrix}
(0)(1) - (2)(-2) \\
(2)(6) - (4)(1) \\
(4)(-2) - (0)(6) 
\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 8 \\ -8 \end{pmatrix}
\]Next, we use any of the three points to solve for the constant D: \[4(-3) + 8(4) + (-8)(-2) + D = 0 \implies D = -44.\]Therefore, the equation of the plane is \(\boxed{2x + 4y - 4z - 44 = 0}.\]

